            <fr:title text="Subsets">Subsets</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p> The most important kind of relationship between sets is the <html:strong>subset</html:strong> relation.</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>17</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/002N/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>002N</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/002N/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Subset">Subset</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>A set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> is a <html:strong>subset</html:strong> of a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ]]></fr:tex> iff: every member of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> is also a member of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ]]></fr:tex>.
There's a symbol for this: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  \subseteq  \Delta ]]></fr:tex> means that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> is a subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>In the above definition, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ]]></fr:tex> are capital Greek letters: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> is Gamma and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ]]></fr:tex> is Delta.
It's common to use lots of different alphabets in logic, with the Greek alphabet probably the most common one other than our own Latin alphabet.
I'll use capital Greek letters like these particularly for sets of things, usually sets of formulas.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
When <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  \subseteq  \Delta ]]></fr:tex>, we know that everything in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> is in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ]]></fr:tex> as well.
There might be some other things also in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ]]></fr:tex> as well, or there might not; that doesn't matter.
(If there isn't anything else in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ]]></fr:tex>, then by extensionality <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ]]></fr:tex> must be the same set.)
</html:p>
            <html:p> Some things to note about subsets:
<html:ul><html:li>There is an important difference between being a <html:em>subset</html:em> of a set and being a <html:em>member</html:em> of the set.
        For example, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{p, q\}]]></fr:tex> is a subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{p, q, r\}]]></fr:tex>, since every member of the former is also a member of the latter.
        But <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{p, q\}]]></fr:tex> is not a member of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{p, q, r\}]]></fr:tex>; only <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex> are members of this set.</html:li>
  <html:li>Every set is a subset of itself.
        For example, consider the set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{p, q \land  r\}]]></fr:tex>.
        This has two members: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q \land  r]]></fr:tex>.
        And both of these members are indeed also members of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{p, q \land  r\}]]></fr:tex>, so the definition of subsethood is met.
        More generally, for any set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex>, all the members of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> are indeed members of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> is always a subset of itself, for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
  <html:li>The empty set is a subset of absolutely any set.
        This might be a surprise, but remember logicians' weird habit number 2!
        To check whether the empty set is a subset of some set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex>, we need to check whether all the members of the empty set are also members of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex>.
        Since there are no members of the empty set, indeed it <html:em>is</html:em> true that all the members of the empty set are members of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex>---no matter what <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> is.
        (Using <fr:link href="/lectures/000F/" title="Logicians' Weird Habit 2" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/000F/" display-uri="000F" type="local">logicians' weird habit number 2</fr:link>, it's even true that all the members of the empty set are square circles, that they're all plants with mammal-like brains, and that they're all behind you right now.)</html:li></html:ul></html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
